Excellent results. The data is clean and ready for training. Let me give you the precise interpretation of each number, flag one discrepancy worth noting, and tell you exactly what to run next.

What Each Number Actually Tells You
G std = 4,569 Pa is the most informative single number in that table. It means the average spatial standard deviation across each 64×64 stiffness map is 4,569 Pa. Given your background range of 800–3,000 Pa and inclusion range of 5,000–45,000 Pa, a per-sample std of 4,569 confirms that inclusions are large and high-contrast on average — not just barely distinguishable from background. For the FNO this is ideal training signal: the model will encounter clear, learnable structure from the very first batch.
Re/Im correlation = −0.02 is effectively zero, which is the physically correct answer. In a properly solved complex Helmholtz system, the real and imaginary displacement components encode phase-quadrature information — they should be orthogonal. A value near zero confirms the solver is computing both components independently, meaning all four input channels carry genuinely distinct information. If this had been −0.98 or +0.98, the model would have been learning from two channels of effectively redundant data.
G range 800–45,000 Pa spanning the full generation range confirms no systematic clipping or truncation at the solver boundary conditions. Cases near the extremes — very soft backgrounds, very stiff inclusions — did not cause the FD matrix to become singular or overflow.

One Discrepancy to Correct
The file size of 4.10 GB contradicts the earlier estimate of 18–22 GB. The 4.10 GB is correct. Here is the actual arithmetic:
X:  50,000 × 4 × 64 × 64 × 4 bytes (float32) = 3.28 GB
Y:  50,000 × 64 × 64 × 4 bytes (float32)      = 0.82 GB
HDF5 overhead + metadata                       ≈ 0.01 GB
Total                                          ≈ 4.10 GB  ✓
The earlier 18–22 GB estimate assumed float64 storage. The good news is that 4.10 GB fits entirely in CPU RAM on Delta (256 GB nodes) and comfortably in A100 GPU memory (80 GB), meaning you can load the entire dataset into memory before training rather than streaming from disk. This will make training significantly faster.

What to Run Right Now
Step 1 — Quick visual spot check before committing to training (2 minutes)
Do this before submitting the GPU job. It takes 10 lines and will immediately surface any phantom generation or solver problem that the numerical checks cannot catch.
python# Run this interactively on the login node (CPU only, 2 min)
import h5py, matplotlib.pyplot as plt, numpy as np

f   = h5py.File("data/mre_synthetic_50000.h5", "r")
idx = [0, 12500, 25000, 37500, 49999]   # span the full dataset

fig, axes = plt.subplots(len(idx), 3, figsize=(9, 15))

for row, i in enumerate(idx):
    X, Y = f["X"][i], f["Y"][i]

    axes[row,0].imshow(X[0], cmap="RdBu_r")   # Re(u) at 60 Hz
    axes[row,0].set_title(f"Re(u)  sample {i}" if row==0 else f"s={i}")

    axes[row,1].imshow(X[2], cmap="RdBu_r")   # Re(u) at 120 Hz
    axes[row,1].set_title("Re(u) 120 Hz" if row==0 else "")

    axes[row,2].imshow(Y, cmap="hot")
    axes[row,2].set_title("G map [Pa]" if row==0 else f"{Y.min():.0f}–{Y.max():.0f} Pa")

    for ax in axes[row]: ax.axis("off")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("data/spot_check.png", dpi=150)
print("Saved data/spot_check.png")
What you must see to proceed:

Column 1: a visible wave pattern propagating left to right with a clear wavelength change where the inclusion sits
Column 2: the same wave at 120 Hz should show roughly half the wavelength — more cycles across the domain
Column 3: a clean elliptical or circular bright region on a darker background

If any of those three conditions look wrong, stop and investigate before submitting the GPU job.

